THE PALE QUEEN'S COMPACT
A 5-Adventure Mini-Campaign
For the Parks Group — Designed for Slow, Story-Driven Play



CAMPAIGN SUMMARY
The party freed Ismara Ice-Born from her prison at Frostmere Barrow, lied to Winterhold about it, and are now traveling with a 4,000-year-old undead genius who is quietly converting Skyrim's living population into components of a ritual that will transfer her consciousness into the land itself. She will become the continent. She cannot be killed. She will also, as a side effect, make it cosmologically impossible for Alduin to return. The party helped make this happen. Now they have to decide what to do about it.
ADVENTURES
5
SESSIONS EST.
10-15
AP EARNED
4
TIER
Apprentice


PART ONE: THE GRAND MYSTERY FRAMEWORK


This campaign is a single, sprawling investigation spread across five adventures. The players begin with almost no information and earn every revelation through exploration, deduction, and consequence. No NPC will explain the plot to them. No convenient scholar knows about the crown. The truth is buried in architecture, behavior, old stone, and Ismara's own presence among them.

Component 1: The Victim & The True Crime
The Victim:
Skyrim's living population, hundreds of ordinary people being marked and consumed as ritual components
Winterhold, nearly dead, its survivors clinging to warmth in two buildings
The concept of a killable Ismara. Once the ritual completes, that dies too

The True Crime:
Ismara is conducting a territorial consciousness transfer ritual. She is marking living people with Atmoran sigil components. Those people freeze in place at specific geographic coordinates across the region, becoming nodes in a grand cognitive matrix. When the ritual reaches completion and is powered by the Eye of Magnus, she will channel her entire consciousness out of the Ice Crown and into the land itself.
Skyrim becomes her phylactery. She becomes the continent. She can manifest anywhere within her borders, she is unkillable because you cannot kill a landmass, and Alduin cannot destroy the world without first destroying her — fighting her on her own ground, which is all ground, forever.
The frozen people do not unfreeze. They melt into the earth. Their souls become part of her distributed intelligence. In her framework she is not killing them. She is elevating them. They become permanent, immortal, constituent parts of something eternal and impossible. She genuinely does not understand why mortals would object to this.

GM NOTE
The party has been watching her place nodes since Adventure 1. Every time they chose not to intervene, someone was condemned. The full picture should arrive in Adventure 4 and the players should look back at every choice they made with new eyes.


Component 2: The Perpetrator & The Motive
Primary Perpetrator: Ismara Ice-Born
Motive: PRESERVATION — she genuinely believes this is the only way to prevent Alduin's return
Motive: SOVEREIGNTY — she was a ruler before the Dragon Cult imprisoned her. She intends to be one again
Motive: SURVIVAL — her cognitive matrix is brilliant but fragile. A body can be destroyed. An Ice Crown can be shattered. A continent cannot

Secondary Perpetrator: The Party
They freed her. They lied about killing her. They have been traveling with her and watching her work
Some of it was coerced. Some of it was choice. The campaign makes no distinction between the two

Opposing Force: The Dragon Cult
They want Alduin to return. Ismara's ritual is a direct cosmological threat to their purpose
They are not the main antagonists. They are pressure. They appear in Adventures 4 and 5 as an obstacle
Their goal in Adventure 5 is identical to what the party may want: stop Ismara. This should feel disgusting

Component 3: The Deception
The Central Lie:
The party told Winterhold they killed Ismara. Winterhold's survivors believe them. Jarl Korir trusts the party completely because they were his agents and they reported success. The cold did not stop. Nobody has connected those two facts yet because nobody is looking — they all believe the monster is dead.

The False Narratives in Play:
"The cold is just Winterhold's bad luck." Korir's position. He cannot afford panic.
"The College's experiments will stabilize things." Savos Aren's position. He is wrong and his attempts are making things measurably worse.
"The frozen people are a disease. Quarantine the afflicted." Windhelm's initial response. Clinical, wrong, and too slow.

Component 4: The Clues
The Rule of Three applies throughout: every major revelation has at least three independent routes to discovery. No single failed roll stops the investigation. No single NPC holds the key.

