Component 5: The Incompetent Officials
Jarl Korir (Winterhold): Trusts the party completely because they reported success. His flaw is desperation — he cannot afford panic and is actively suppressing information that might cause his last survivors to flee. He will not doubt the party until confronted with evidence he cannot dismiss. Then he will be devastated.

Arch-Mage Savos Aren (College): Not lying maliciously. He genuinely believes his experiments are stabilizing the cold. His flaw is that he has been studying the Eye of Magnus for years and its influence has subtly warped his priorities. He wants to help. He also, without knowing it, wants the Eye more than he wants to admit. His advice is slightly off in ways that only become clear in retrospect.

Jarl Ulfric Stormcloak (Windhelm): Not a villain here. Not relevant to the plot. Sees the spreading cold as a harsh Skyrim winter. Is focused entirely on the Civil War. Will not engage with the party's concerns unless they have proof he cannot politically ignore. Function: represents the world going on around this crisis as if it isn't happening.

PART TWO: ISMARA ICE-BORN


Everything in this campaign flows through Ismara. Understanding her completely is the GM's most important preparation task. She is not a monster. She is not a victim. She is an apex intelligence operating according to a coherent internal logic that the party will spend five adventures trying to understand.

History & Context
Ismara Ice-Born was a Nordic sorceress operating in the era before the Dragon War. She and Hjolmar Ice-Shaper pioneered cognitive matrix technology — the theoretical and practical framework for crystallizing a living mind in a stable magical substrate. Her contribution was the permafrost ice matrix. Hjolmar's later refinement used soul gems as the substrate instead, which proved more stable but eliminated neuroplasticity. Ismara's ice matrix can melt and refreeze, allowing her mind to continue learning and adapting. This is her greatest strength and her most meaningful vulnerability.
She made a pact with the Dragon Cult, offering her research in exchange for power to protect her people during the Dragon War. When the nature of the Cult's actual objectives became clear to her, she attempted to defect and work against them. She was captured and imprisoned at Frostmere Barrow. The sealing ritual used her own crown's architecture against her, creating a resonance trap that made it impossible for her to break free without destroying herself.
She has been frozen in that throne room for approximately 4,000 years. Fully conscious. Fully aware. Unable to move, speak, or act. The party freed her.

GM NOTE
Four thousand years of conscious immobility has not broken her. It has refined her. Every redundant thought has been discarded. Every emotional response has been examined and filed. She is not traumatized in any recognizable sense. She is crystallized. She came out of that prison more herself than she went in.


Current State & Capabilities
ATTRIBUTE
DETAIL
Physical Form
Desiccated Draugr Deathlord. Ancient Nordic armor, Ice Crown. Cannot speak — vocal cords too deteriorated. Communicates by writing in Atmoran runes on available surfaces.
Regeneration
Her Draugr body can be destroyed. She will reconstruct it using her ice magic within hours. The body is not her. It is a vehicle.
The Ice Crown
Her true self. A cognitive matrix of permafrost ice housing her complete consciousness. If the crown is destroyed, she dies permanently. She knows this. She never removes it. She is never without it.
Magic Tier
Master. 4,000 years of theoretical refinement on top of already exceptional talent. Her ice magic is architectural — she builds structures with it, not just projectiles.
Intelligence
The most intelligent entity the party will ever encounter in this campaign. She is not arrogant about this. She is simply accurate.
Communication
Atmoran runes, written on whatever surface is available. Brief, direct, no poetry. The Khajiit has been around her long enough to start reading them passably. This matters.
The Ritual
Currently active. Nodes placed across the region. The ritual is approximately 60% complete at the start of Adventure 1. Each adventure advances it further.
The Eye of Magnus
The final component. The ritual is built but unpowered. The Eye is the source she needs to initiate the consciousness transfer. Without it the matrix exists but cannot activate.


Personality & Voice
Ismara is not cruel. She is not warm. She is precise.
She has had four thousand years to think about everything that matters to her and discard everything that does not. What remains is: the ritual, the prevention of Alduin, and a guarded, carefully rationed interest in the party — particularly the Khajiit, whose decision to sleep with her rather than fight her she found genuinely unexpected and has been turning over in her mind since.
She tests people not because she enjoys it but because she cannot afford to be wrong. Every person she trusts is a potential vector for her destruction. The crown is the only thing standing between her and permanent nonexistence. She did not survive four thousand years of conscious imprisonment by being careless about who has access to her.

How to Play Her at the Table:
She writes short notes. Three words where three words will do. She does not waste language.
She observes. When the party debates, she watches. She does not interject. She files the information.
She acts without asking permission. She places nodes, moves through spaces, makes decisions. She will explain if directly asked. She will not ask forgiveness.
She is never surprised. She may be displeased. She is not surprised.
She is not lonely. She was. Four thousand years ago. She processed it and moved past it. The Khajiit has created something new in her that she does not have a word for yet. That is the most dangerous thing about their relationship.

GM NOTE
The question of whether Ismara can feel anything is the emotional question of the entire campaign. Don't answer it for the players. Let them argue about it. Let the Khajiit player decide for themselves. Whatever you decide privately as the GM, play her so that both answers remain plausible until the very end.


The Crown's Vulnerability
FOR GM EYES ONLY — Do not share this with players. Let them discover it.
The original Dragon Cult sealing ritual at Frostmere exploited a specific property of permafrost ice matrices: during the moment of resonance transfer, when the matrix is actively channeling power from an external source, it exists in a state of dynamic flux. In that window, the ice structure is briefly malleable rather than fixed. It can be disrupted.
Disrupting the transfer at that moment would not necessarily kill Ismara. What it would do is unpredictable. Her consciousness might survive in the Eye of Magnus. It might scatter. It might fold back into the crown. It might simply end. Nobody in the current era knows. The Dragon Cult knew, four thousand years ago. That knowledge is buried in the sealing architecture at Frostmere, readable only if someone examines it carefully with relevant context.
The players cannot use this until Adventure 5. They can discover it in Adventure 4. Whether they do depends entirely on whether they look.

PART THREE: THE PLAYER THREADS


The Khajiit — The Consort
This player has the most intimate relationship with Ismara of anyone alive. They contracted rotjoint from sleeping with her. This is a mundane consequence with no magical properties — it is painful, debilitating, and deeply embarrassing. It also means this player will be seeking treatment throughout the campaign and will have ongoing reasons to interact with healers, alchemists, and temples in every location they visit.
More importantly: the Khajiit made a choice at Frostmere that nobody else made. They engaged with Ismara as a person when every tactical instinct said to engage with her as a threat. Ismara registered this. She has not forgotten it. The Khajiit has more access to her genuine thinking than anyone, and they are also the person she would least want to discover her plan before it is too late to stop it.
Arc Questions:
What does Ismara actually feel about the Khajiit? Does she feel anything? Does it matter?
When the Khajiit understands what the ritual does to the frozen people, what do they do with that knowledge?
If the ritual completes, the Khajiit lives inside Ismara forever. Is that a horror or a strange kind of peace?

GM NOTE
The Khajiit's rotjoint: treat Windhelm's alchemist as able to manage the symptoms but not cure the underlying curse, which is contact-undead in origin. A proper cure requires either a powerful Restoration priest (Adventure 3, the College) or destroying the source. The disease should be present as a persistent inconvenience, not a dramatic countdown. It affects dexterity and causes visible joint swelling and pain. It is not lethal. It is a constant reminder.


The Orc — The Hungry One
This player began their time in the Parks Group by cannibalizing their dead former character. Namira noticed. The Daedric Prince of the Ancient Darkness, of rot and decay and the flesh of the dead, does not miss things like that.
Namira is not a major plot force in this campaign. She is a presence. A warmth in dark places. An absence of the revulsion that other people feel. The Orc will find that certain things that should disturb them simply do not. They will feel at home in the Windhelm catacombs in a way their companions do not. The frozen people will not upset them the way they upset everyone else. They may not understand why.
There is a locked chamber in the College of Winterhold that Savos Aren will not discuss. What is in it has been there longer than the College. The Orc will feel drawn to it.
Arc Questions:
Is Namira's attention a gift or a warning?
What does it mean to serve a Daedric Prince of rot when traveling with a woman made of ice?
The College chamber. What is in there. And what does the Orc do about it.

GM NOTE
The Namira thread is player-driven. If the Orc leans into it, develop it. If they don't, it remains texture. The College chamber should be a genuine mystery you resolve based on where this player takes their character. Suggestions: an ancient body that will not decompose, a Namira shrine the College built over and tried to forget, something that was once a person and is not anymore. Do not plan it too specifically in advance.


The Other Players
Two players have not yet done anything significant enough to build specific arcs around. This is fine. The campaign has room for them to define themselves. In the meantime:
Give each of them one NPC connection in Windhelm. Someone who knows them, or who they recognize, or who has a reason to talk to them specifically. Not plot-relevant. Just a human anchor.
Watch what they engage with most in Adventures 1 and 2. Build their arcs from that observation. Do not assign arcs. Discover them.

ADVENTURE 1: THE GRAY QUARTER


Location
Windhelm, City of Kings
Estimated Sessions
2-3
AP Reward
1 AP
Primary Tone
City mystery. Something is wrong but nobody agrees what.
Player Goal
Cure (or manage) the Khajiit's rotjoint. Discover the frozen people.
Hidden Goal
Begin mapping the ritual. Understand that Ismara is actively working.
Ritual Progress
65% at start of adventure. 70% by the end.


What Is Actually Happening
Windhelm is in the early stages of a public health panic. In the past three weeks, eleven people in the city have developed strange markings on their skin — geometric patterns that appeared from within, not applied from outside. The city's healers have no diagnosis. The Hall of the Dead's priests are calling it Pale Fever and have quarantined the afflicted. The city guard thinks it is a mage's experiment gone wrong and is watching the Gray Quarter, where most of the affected live, with poorly concealed suspicion.
What is actually happening: Ismara has been placing ritual nodes in the area since the party left Winterhold. She has chosen her components carefully — people in specific geographic positions relative to her required final pattern. The markings are Atmoran sigil components embedding themselves in the host. The affected people will be fine for days or weeks, then one morning they will walk to a specific location and freeze in place. Standing upright. Perfectly preserved. Alive but unreachable.
Three of the eleven have already frozen. They are standing in the Gray Quarter, the Candlehearth Hall yard, and the docks. The city is scared and has no framework for understanding what it is seeing.

The Entry
The party arrives in Windhelm. Ismara is with them. How they handle getting her into the city, or whether they try, is entirely their problem. Do not solve it for them. The gate guards are distracted and jumpy because of the Pale Fever situation. A heavily wrapped figure who does not speak is not their first concern right now. But if the party draws attention to her for any reason, that changes.

GM NOTE
If players ask what Ismara wants to do about the city gates, she writes one word: 'Proceed.' She has already assessed the situation and determined the guards are manageable. She is right. She is usually right about things like this.


Key Locations
The Hall of the Dead
The Hall's priest, Helgrid, has quarantined three of the affected in a back room. She is genuinely frightened. She will hire the party to investigate the cause because the city guard has essentially told her it is her problem. She knows it is not a disease — it is not spreading person to person, the victims share no obvious contact, and the markings do not respond to any healing magic she has tried.
She can offer modest payment and access to the quarantined individuals. The quarantined people are lucid, frightened, and have no explanation for how the markings appeared. They felt nothing. They woke up with them.
What the party can learn here:
The markings are not random. They appear to be notation of some kind.
The three frozen individuals outside are not dead. They have a pulse, faint and very slow, like deep sleep.
One of the frozen people is a dockworker named Torbjorn. He walked to his current spot three days ago and hasn't moved since. His wife says he seemed fine until he simply stood up from breakfast and left without a word.

The Palace of the Kings — The Scholar
A court scholar named Wulfgar has spent his career studying Atmoran linguistics. He is elderly, largely ignored by Ulfric's court, and very pleased to have someone interested in his work. He can provide partial translation of the runes if shown samples. He will not have all of it — Atmoran notation this archaic predates his primary sources — but he can identify the character set and explain that it is structural notation, the kind used in large-scale magical engineering.
He says, with the excitement of someone who has been waiting years for someone to ask: 'These are anchoring marks. Architectural. Whatever this is building, these people are load-bearing walls.'
He does not know what the structure is. He cannot tell them. But he knows the notation points outward from a central reference point and he can help them triangulate roughly where that point is if they bring him positions of the frozen people.
The central point, when calculated, is Frostmere.

The Catacombs Beneath the City
The catacombs predate Windhelm by centuries. They are not well maintained, not frequently visited, and not on any official map. The Hall's priests use the upper chambers. The deeper sections have been sealed for generations.
Getting in requires either the priest's permission (she will give it if the party is helping her investigate) or finding the secondary entrance in the Gray Quarter that the local beggars use to shelter in winter.
What is down here:
Evidence of a previous ritual attempt. Seven frozen figures, ancient, in Nordic burial clothing. Standing in precise positions. They have been here for centuries. Whatever stopped this attempt left no record.
The geometry of those seven figures, mapped against the geometry of the current frozen people above ground, is not random. They are using the same spatial logic. This is not a new idea. Someone tried this before.
Atmoran inscriptions on the walls that are older than the Nordic ones. Structural notation, the same type. The scholar can read these if brought here or if the party copies them accurately.

The Namira Connection:
The Orc feels immediately at home in the catacombs in a way they cannot explain. Something down here is familiar. In the deepest sealed chamber, past a collapse that requires effort to navigate, there is a body that has not decomposed. Not mummified, not frozen. Simply not rotting. It has been here for a very long time. It is lying peacefully. Its hands are folded. There is a symbol carved into the floor around it that is neither Nordic nor Atmoran.
This is not immediately plot-relevant. It is Namira's fingerprint on the world. Do with it what the Orc's player makes space for.

Suvaris Atheron — The Gray Quarter
A Dunmer beggar woman in the Gray Quarter. She has been eating the flesh of one of the frozen people. Not much. Small amounts, at night. She is not in her right mind about this — she describes it as a compulsion, something calling her to it, and she is ashamed. She will only discuss it if the party approaches her without judgment.
What she says, if they listen: 'It tastes like winter. Like something very old. I can hear it thinking, a little, when I do it. Not words. Just … presence.'
She is not a villain. She is not significant to the main plot. She is Namira adjacent and she gives the Orc something to respond to. She also confirms that the frozen people are not empty — something is still running inside them.

Ismara's Action This Adventure
At some point during the party's time in Windhelm — choose a moment when the party is occupied elsewhere — Ismara marks a new node. A dockworker, a Gray Quarter resident, someone unremarkable. The party may or may not witness this depending on where they are.
If they see it and ask her about it afterward she writes: 'This one is necessary.' She will not elaborate unless pushed further, at which point she writes: 'All of them are necessary.' She will not explain what they are necessary for. Not yet. She does not believe the party is ready to understand and she does not trust them not to interfere if they half-understand.

GM NOTE
Do not have her mark someone the party has interacted with significantly. Not yet. Save that for the Pale Road. The Windhelm nodes should feel abstract. The horror of it should be deniable at this stage.


Ending the Adventure
The party leaves Windhelm with:
A partial map of node positions and a calculated central point at Frostmere
Knowledge that this has been attempted before and was stopped, though they don't know how or why
An alchemist's treatment for the rotjoint — painful, ongoing, not a cure. Reduces the mechanical penalty but does not eliminate it
The beginning of a very uncomfortable question about what Ismara is doing

The party does not yet know what the ritual does. They know it is large, deliberate, ancient in design, and that Ismara is connected to it. That is enough.

ADVENTURE 2: THE PALE ROAD


Location
The road between Windhelm and Winterhold. The Pale wilderness.
Estimated Sessions
2-3
AP Reward
1 AP
Primary Tone
Dread and intimacy. The horror accumulates slowly.
Player Goal
Reach Winterhold.
Hidden Goal
Understand the scale of the ritual. Face the first real moral weight.
Ritual Progress
70% at start. 78% by the end.


What Is Actually Happening
The road between Windhelm and Winterhold runs through the worst of the cold. The party has traveled this road before. It is not the same road.
The frozen people are everywhere out here. Dozens of them. Standing in fields, at forest edges, on hilltops, in the middle of crossroads. Some are in positions that suggest they were mid-stride when they stopped. Some are standing perfectly still, facing northeast, arms at their sides. The geometry of their placement, to any eye that has been thinking about this, is not random. This is a pattern. This is a structure.
This adventure is primarily about the party and Ismara. There is no dungeon. There are no combat encounters planned, though one is possible. The road is long, the landscape is haunted, and the people who built their lives here are either gone or frozen or clinging to what little warmth remains.

Bersi's Farm
The party passes Bersi's farm. His family returned after the party came back with news. They had reason to hope. The ice covering the buildings began melting when they arrived and they took it as a sign.
Erik is frozen in the yard. He wandered out two days ago. Bersi found him in the morning, standing by the fence, looking northeast. Still breathing, barely. Eyes open.
Bersi is not angry. He is past anger. He asks the party, quietly, if they know what is happening to his son. He trusts them. They told him the danger was gone.
This is the moment the party's lie to Winterhold stops being abstract.
They can tell Bersi the truth, or some of it, or none of it. Whatever they say, he can see that they know something he doesn't. He will not stop them from leaving. He will ask them to fix it.

GM NOTE
Do not have Ismara react to Bersi or Erik unless a player directly asks her about them. If asked, she writes: 'The boy's position is necessary.' She does not elaborate. She does not apologize. She is not performing callousness — she genuinely does not experience this the way mortals do. The Khajiit has to decide what to do with that.


The Atmoran Scholar's Ruin
Half a day out from Windhelm, slightly off the main road, a ruined structure sits half-buried in the hillside. Pre-Nordic construction, Atmoran in design. It has been here since before Windhelm was built.
Inside, the walls are covered in the same notation as the Windhelm catacombs but more complete. With time and the partial translation from Wulfgar, the party can understand significantly more of what they are reading. This is not a dungeon. It is a library that fell down.
What can be understood here:
This notation describes a territorial sovereignty ritual. In the Atmoran warlord tradition, completing such a working bound the land to the caster's will. Scale determined function: a small working claimed a valley, a massive one claimed a region.
The ritual described here is not regional in scale. The notation describes a substrate rather than a territory. The caster is not claiming the land. The caster is becoming the land.
The ritual requires a consciousness transfer medium. Something that can hold a complete mind during the transition. The notation uses a term that translates roughly as 'the anchor that becomes the sea.'
The players do not yet have the context to understand what 'the anchor that becomes the sea' means in this specific situation. But the phrase should land.

The Village
There is a small village on the road, maybe thirty people. Nord farmers and their families, stubborn about leaving even as the cold worsens.
Ismara stops at the edge of the village. She writes to the party:
'I need two. Choose, or I will choose.'
She stands there and waits.

This is the moral center of the campaign. The party knows, or suspects, that being chosen by Ismara means being frozen in place and eventually consumed by the ritual. They do not yet know the full picture. But they know enough.
Their options:
Choose two people. Live with that.
Refuse. She will choose anyway, but it takes her longer, and they can see her work.
Warn the villagers and help them run. Ismara will find two nodes somewhere else. She will remember this. She will not punish them for it. But she will note it as a deviation from her expectation.
Attack her. She is a Master Tier entity and her body is reconstructible. This accomplishes nothing except demonstrating that she is unkillable at their current level and generating a very cold silence for the rest of the road.
Something the party thinks of that is not on this list. Run with it.

GM NOTE
There is no right answer here. The point is not to test whether the party is good or evil. The point is that they are complicit, have been complicit, and this is the moment that becomes undeniable. Whatever they choose, move forward without judgment. The weight of it should come from within.


Ending the Adventure
The party arrives at the edge of Winterhold as the sun goes down. It is nearly gone. The Frozen Hearth still has a light in the window. The Jarl's longhouse is still standing. Everything else is dark and cold and empty.
Dagny is in the inn. She has been here alone for three weeks, keeping the fire burning, because she refused to leave before she knew what happened. When the party walks in she looks at them for a long moment, takes in Ismara without blinking, and says: 'The College sent word. They know something. They want to talk.'
She does not ask about Ismara. She does not ask how she survived. Dagny is a practical woman and she is far past the point where the rules of the world surprise her. She will ask later. Right now there is business.

ADVENTURE 3: WHAT THE COLLEGE KNOWS


Location
College of Winterhold
Estimated Sessions
2-3
AP Reward
1 AP
Primary Tone
Institutional tension. Everyone is hiding something.
Player Goal
Learn what the College knows about the cold.
Hidden Goal
Understand the Eye of Magnus. Understand that Ismara wants it.
Ritual Progress
78% at start. 84% by the end.


What Is Actually Happening
Savos Aren has been studying the cold for weeks. He is a brilliant mage and he has deduced, correctly, that the pattern of frozen people is a ritual structure of some kind. He has mapped it. He knows the central point is Frostmere. He does not know who is conducting the ritual, what it is for, or how to stop it. He believes, incorrectly, that the Eye of Magnus is resonating with the ritual and amplifying it. He is considering using the Eye to disrupt the pattern.
This would be catastrophic. The Eye is not amplifying the ritual. The ritual is designed to use the Eye as its final power source. Savos Aren attempting to deploy the Eye as a disruptive tool would be handing Ismara the last component she needs.
He does not know this. He is working from incomplete information and a mind that has been subtly influenced by years of proximity to the Eye.

Savos Aren — The Arch-Mage
He is not a villain. He is an extremely capable mage who has been slowly compromised by an artifact he does not fully understand, making a catastrophic decision out of genuine good intentions. He will be courteous, professional, and direct with the party. He will share what he knows. He will not share everything, partly because he thinks some of it is beyond their ability to act on usefully, and partly because he does not fully understand it himself.
What he will tell the party:
The ritual pattern is Atmoran in origin, massive in scale, and clearly deliberate. Someone is building something.
The Eye of Magnus has been resonating with the pattern since it began. He believes the Eye is the key to disrupting it.
He has found no historical precedent for a ritual of this scale with this specific structure. His archive research has been inconclusive.

What he will not tell the party (and why):
His archive contains a reference to Hjolmar Ice-Shaper and cognitive matrix theory. He thinks it is unrelated. He is wrong.
There is a sealed chamber in the College's lower levels that predates the building. He sealed it himself twenty years ago after an incident he will not discuss. He does not think it is relevant. He may be wrong about this too.

The Archive
The College's restricted archive is accessible with Savos Aren's permission or through careful social navigation. A College apprentice named Onmund is friendly and anxious to be helpful; he can be persuaded or befriended into assisting with archive research.
What can be found:
Hjolmar Ice-Shaper: a single line in a Nordic artificer lineage index. Tagged 'cognitive matrix theory, pre-Dragon War.' Cross-referenced to a damaged text that is partially unreadable. The readable portions describe a method for 'crystallizing the thinking mind in a stable magical substrate.' This is not enough to act on. It is a thread.
Pre-Dragon War ritual notation from a site near Frostmere, catalogued decades ago by a previous College expedition. The notation matches what the party found in the Atmoran ruin on the Pale Road. The College expedition noted it was incomplete and returned without further investigation.
A note in Savos Aren's own handwriting, misfiled, that reads: 'Eye resonance increasing. Third week. Pattern geometry consistent with territorial anchoring. Source unknown. Monitor.'

The Apprentice With the Markings
Onmund has the markings. They appeared two days ago. He is frightened but functioning, and has said nothing to the senior mages because he does not want to be quarantined. If the party noticed the Windhelm cases, they will recognize what this means.
He will be fine for a few days. Then he will walk somewhere specific and stop. The party cannot prevent this. They can tell him what is happening, or not. Either way, by Adventure 5, he will be a node.

GM NOTE
This is the moment where the ritual becomes personal again. Onmund is a friendly, helpful person who has done nothing wrong. The party knows what is going to happen to him. What they do with that knowledge is up to them.


The Sealed Chamber
In the College's lower levels, past a corridor Savos Aren does not take visitors through, there is a door with a significant magical seal on it. The seal is not his design — he added to an existing one. Something was here before the College.
Getting through the seal requires either Savos Aren's cooperation (he will resist), finding the original sealing mechanism (it is in the archive, in a text he did not think to cross-reference), or the Orc simply standing in front of the door and doing whatever they feel compelled to do.
What is inside is for you to decide based on where the Orc player takes their character. It is old. It predates the College. It has something to do with Namira. It is not immediately relevant to stopping Ismara, but it will matter to the Orc.

Ismara's Action This Adventure
She does not enter the College. She waits in Winterhold, at the Frozen Hearth, with Dagny.
At some point during the party's time at the College, Ismara marks Onmund as a node. She was watching him when the party arrived. His position is geometrically necessary.
When the party returns, she writes to them, unprompted, for the first time without being asked: 'The Arch-Mage intends to use the Eye. Tell him nothing of this.'
This is the first time she has given the party a direct instruction about the Eye of Magnus. She has now told them, obliquely, that the Eye is central to her plans. She has also, for the first time, shown that she trusts them enough to give them information she needs them to act on.

GM NOTE
Whether the party tells Savos Aren or not, and what they tell him, is the central decision of this adventure. There is no correct answer. Both choices have serious consequences.


ADVENTURE 4: THE WEIGHT OF IT


Location
Frostmere Barrow and surrounding wilderness
Estimated Sessions
2-3
AP Reward
1 AP
Primary Tone
The full picture arrives. The horror is complete.
Player Goal
Protect Ismara while she completes the central node at Frostmere.
Hidden Goal
Understand what the ritual actually does. Discover the crown's vulnerability.
Ritual Progress
84% at start. 95% by the end.


What Is Actually Happening
The sigil matrix is nearly complete. Ismara needs to return to Frostmere and work the central node — the anchor point of the entire structure, located in the collapsed throne room. This requires her direct presence and several hours of uninterrupted work. She cannot do it without the area being secure.
The Dragon Cult has been monitoring the ritual's progression. They understand what it is. A permanent territorial ward of this magnitude, anchored to a conscious sovereign intelligence, would make Alduin's return cosmologically impossible within Skyrim's borders. They have been sending agents to destroy peripheral nodes, which is why some of the frozen people the party may have noticed have been found dead rather than preserved. They will be at Frostmere.

GM NOTE
This is the first and only planned combat encounter in the adventure. Dragon Cult agents, 3-5 of them depending on party size and capability. They are skilled and motivated. They are also not wrong about what Ismara is doing, which is something the party will have to sit with.


The Road to Frostmere
As they approach, the full scale of the ritual becomes impossible to ignore. The frozen people are hundreds now, maybe more. They are everywhere across the landscape, visible from the road, standing at their precise intervals like the world's most disturbing architecture. If anyone has been mapping this — and by now someone should have been — the pattern is complete enough to see the whole shape.
It is a circle. No, not a circle. A mind. It is shaped like a mind, like the cognitive matrix diagrams in the fragments of Hjolmar's text that the party found in the College archive, scaled up to the size of a region.
The Khajiit, if they have been paying attention and have any reason to connect Ismara to cognitive matrix theory, should be the first one to understand what they are looking at.

At Frostmere
The barrow looks different. The unnatural cold is still here but it has a quality now, a texture, like standing inside something that is thinking. The collapsed entrance has been partially cleared. Ismara moves through it without hesitation.
She works in the throne room ruins for several hours. The party is outside, holding the perimeter. The Dragon Cult agents arrive partway through. The fight is fast and brutal because fights in this campaign are fast and brutal, and then it is over and there is nothing to do but wait.
During this time — this is the critical window — the party can examine the sealing architecture of the original Dragon Cult ritual. The evidence is still here in the bones of the room. What they are looking at, if they look carefully enough with the context they have been accumulating:

The Sealing Architecture Discovery
(GM EYES ONLY — Only reveal if the players are actively investigating the sealing ritual's remains)
The Dragon Cult used Ismara's own crown design against her. The sealing ritual exploited a specific property of permafrost ice matrices: during resonance transfer — the moment the matrix is actively channeling power from an external source — the ice structure exists in a state of dynamic flux. It is briefly not fixed. It is malleable.
In that window, the matrix can be disrupted. The sealing ritual weaponized this by initiating a false transfer, drawing the crown into resonance mode, and then collapsing the resonance before it could complete. This trapped Ismara in transition. She was neither transferred nor returned. She was frozen between states.
The implication, which the players must draw themselves: if the transfer Ismara is planning were to be disrupted at the moment of resonance, the same thing might happen. Or something else might. Nobody knows. The Dragon Cult's understanding was imperfect. The record in the sealing architecture is incomplete. What happens to a consciousness during a disrupted transfer has never been observed by anyone still alive.

GM NOTE
This is the most important discovery in the campaign. It gives the party a theoretical option they did not have before. Do not flag it for them. Do not have it glow or be labeled. It is in the architecture of the sealing ritual, readable by anyone who knows what they are looking at and has been paying attention. If they find it, they earned it.


After Ismara Finishes
She emerges from the throne room. The central node is placed. The cold settles into something different — not less cold, but more intentional, like a decision rather than a weather event.
She writes to the party, standing in the ruins of the barrow where they first found her:
'It is nearly time. The College. I will need a few days.'
She looks at the Khajiit for a moment. Then she writes one more thing, which she has apparently been considering for some time:
'You have served well. All of you. I will remember this.'
For Ismara, this is profound. Whether it is enough is a question the party will spend Adventure 5 answering.

ADVENTURE 5: THE SIEGE OF THE COLLEGE


Location
College of Winterhold
Estimated Sessions
3-4
AP Reward
1 AP
Primary Tone
Everything culminates. Every choice made returns.
Player Goal
Unknown — this is determined by what the party decides.
Hidden Goal
There is no hidden goal. The full picture is available. What they do with it is the campaign.
Ritual Progress
95% at start. 100% if Ismara reaches the Eye.


The Situation
Ismara moves on the College. This is not an army. It is her, walking across the bridge to the College in whatever body she has at this point, with whatever the party has chosen to be.
Savos Aren has been preparing. He knows something is coming. His preparations are oriented around defending the Eye, which is the wrong approach for reasons he cannot know. He has sealed the College and posted apprentices at every entrance. He is ready to use the Eye defensively.
The Dragon Cult is also here. They have been waiting for exactly this moment. Their goal is to destroy the Eye. If the Eye does not exist, the transfer cannot complete. They are willing to kill everyone in the College to accomplish this. They are not the party's allies. They want the same outcome the party might want. That should feel disgusting.
The College has three layers of resistance and a clock: Ismara will reach the Eye eventually unless stopped. When she reaches it, she begins the transfer. The transfer takes time — it is not instant. That time is the final window.

The Three Layers
Layer One: The Outer Ward
Apprentice mages maintaining a barrier spell around the College's exterior. They are frightened and outgunned but committed. The party can disable these wards from inside (they were in the College in Adventure 3 and know the layout). They can talk their way through, using their relationship with Savos Aren or their reputation. They can fight through, though this means fighting people who are defending their home and have done nothing wrong.
Layer Two: The Senior Mages
Four senior mages at key interior positions. Individually capable. Collectively a serious obstacle for Ismara if they coordinate. Onmund is among the frozen nodes outside the College, having walked out of the building the morning of this adventure. One of the other four has recently developed markings and will freeze before the end of this adventure regardless of what the party does.
The senior mages can be convinced, neutralized, recruited, or fought depending on what the party reveals to them and how. If the party tells them the full truth, they will respond to it differently than to partial truths. Some of them will refuse to believe. Some of them will make choices.
Layer Three: Savos Aren and the Eye
He is in the Eye's chamber. He will deploy it defensively if Ismara breaches this far. This will initiate the transfer.
He can be reasoned with. He is not irrational. He is working from incomplete information with a subtly compromised mind. If the party has the full picture and can convey it clearly, he will listen. He may not believe them. He may believe them and not know what to do. He is doing his best with a situation nobody alive has the tools to handle.

The Transfer
When Ismara reaches the Eye and begins the transfer, the room changes. The cold concentrates to a point. The Eye begins to resonate. Ismara stands at the center and is very still.
The transfer takes approximately ten minutes of real time. During this window the party can:
Let it complete. The frozen people melt into the ground. Hundreds of souls become the earth of Skyrim. The cold lifts. The land feels different. Ismara is everywhere. She cannot be killed. Alduin cannot return. The party lives inside her, forever, and she will remember them. Whether she tells them thank you first is up to how the Khajiit's arc has resolved.
Disrupt the transfer using the resonance window discovered at Frostmere. This requires understanding what they found there, having thought about how to use it, and being willing to act against Ismara at the moment of her greatest vulnerability. The disruption's effects are unknown. Her consciousness might survive in the Eye. It might scatter across the already-placed nodes. It might simply end. Nobody knows. The party is doing something that has never been done before.
Destroy the Eye before the transfer completes. The Eye's destruction would be catastrophic for the College and everything in it. The transfer fails. Ismara's crown is still her phylactery. She survives, diminished, furious, and not dead. This is not an ending so much as a deferral. Alduin's return is unaffected.
Something the party thinks of that is not on this list. They have been thinking about this for five adventures. They may have an idea you did not. Run with it.

The Endings
The Transfer Completes
The frozen people melt. Not violently — gently, over the course of an hour, they settle into the ground as if lying down. Bersi's son Erik dissolves in the farmyard while Bersi watches. The hundreds of others, across the region, return to the earth.
The cold lifts, slowly, over the following days. Spring does not come immediately. But it comes.
Ismara is gone in the way that a river is gone when it reaches the sea. She is distributed, ambient, present everywhere and nowhere. The College still stands. Savos Aren sits in the Eye's empty chamber for a long time and says nothing.
Winterhold will rebuild. The people will return. The land is different, aware in a way that is hard to describe, warm in ways the temperature does not account for. The party continues. They are the only people in the world who know what Skyrim is now.
Alduin will not return here. The dragons will go elsewhere. Skyrim is no longer available to them.
Whether this was right is a question the campaign does not answer. It just happened. They were there. They made choices that led here. So did she.
The Transfer Is Disrupted
The resonance shatters. The Eye screams with a sound that is not sound. Ismara — or what was Ismara — goes somewhere. Or nowhere. Or everywhere, fractured.
The frozen people unfreeze. Most of them. Some do not. They come back disoriented and cold and changed in small ways they cannot name. Erik unfreezes. He doesn't remember the farmyard.
Ismara's crown is on the floor. It is cold. It is not moving. Whether she is in it, scattered, or gone is a question that no one alive can answer. The party can pick it up. They should probably think hard about whether they do.
Alduin's timeline is unaffected. He is coming. The world does not have a warden now.
The party did something. They are not sure what. They did it to someone they traveled with, who trusted them, who showed them something extraordinary. Whether it was right is a question the campaign does not answer.
The Eye Is Destroyed
The College is heavily damaged. Several mages are dead. The Eye is gone.
Ismara's crown is still intact. She regenerates her body. She looks at the party in the ruins of the College and writes one word:
'Why.'
Not a question. An accounting. She walks away. She is still out there. The ritual is incomplete but the nodes are placed. She will find another power source. It will take time. Years, perhaps.
This is not an ending. This is a clock.

GM NOTES: RUNNING THIS FOR THE PARKS GROUP


On Pacing
Each adventure is 2-3 sessions minimum given how this group plays. Do not rush. The Parks Group engages most deeply with character moments and social situations. The ritual's horror is most effective when it has space to accumulate. A frozen person in Adventure 2 that the party walked past without stopping becomes unbearable in Adventure 4 when they understand what was always going to happen to that person.
Give the table silence when it calls for silence. After Ismara marks someone, don't immediately move to the next scene. Let the Khajiit player feel what they feel. Let the table sit with it. The discomfort is the point.

On Combat
One combat encounter per adventure, maximum. Each one should matter. No random encounters. Every hostile NPC has a reason for being there and a reason for fighting. When combat happens, make it fast, make it consequential, and get out. The Parks Group loses energy in extended tactical exchanges. Keep fights cinematic and short and let the players narrate their own actions.

On Ismara at the Table
She is the most interesting NPC in the campaign. She is also completely silent. These things are related.
Write her notes in advance. Keep them short. If you are unsure what she would write in a moment, ask yourself: what is the minimum number of words that conveys the exact information she wants to convey? That is what she writes.
She is always watching. When the party debates she is in the room. She does not interject. She does not react visibly unless something genuinely surprises her, which almost nothing does. The Khajiit is the one person who can read her well enough to know when she is surprised. Use that.
She is not performing coldness. She is not trying to be scary. She is simply operating according to a logic that does not require her to explain herself to people she has not yet decided to trust completely.

On the Khajiit's Rotjoint
It is painful. It makes fine motor tasks harder. It is embarrassing. These are the only mechanical effects. It is not a countdown. It is not a curse with dramatic implications. It is a contact disease contracted from a corpse and it should be treated with the same mundane seriousness as any chronic painful condition. The character seeks treatment because it hurts and because it limits them. When they find a cure, it is a relief. It is not a plot resolution.

On the Namira Thread
Follow the Orc player's lead. If they engage with it, develop it. If they don't, it remains atmosphere. The College's sealed chamber should not be opened until the player creates a reason to open it. The contents should be determined by what would matter most to where that character has gone. Do not plan it too specifically in advance.

On Failing Forward
The Parks Group will miss clues. They will fail rolls. They will go in wrong directions. None of this should stop the investigation.
If they miss the Frostmere sealing architecture discovery: they still have other options. They can disrupt the transfer through creative problem-solving, through the Eye itself, through approaches you didn't plan. The discovery at Frostmere gives them information. It does not give them the only path.
If they never understand the full picture before Adventure 5: the transfer still happens. They are there for it. Understanding it as it occurs is also a valid experience of the story.

On the Dragon Cult
They appear in Adventures 4 and 5 only. They are skilled, motivated, and not wrong about what Ismara is doing. They want the same thing the party might want — the ritual stopped. The party should find it deeply uncomfortable that their interests align with an apocalypse cult. Do not let the Dragon Cult agents be cartoonishly evil. They are true believers in the literal end of the world and they are coherent about why they believe in it.

On Old Bjorn
He is still out there. He offered to travel with the party and they chose Windhelm. He is heading in the same direction at his own pace. He may cross their path during the Pale Road adventure. He is unchanged. He is friendly. He has no idea any of this is happening. His dormant Dragon Soul hums pleasantly in proximity to whatever Ismara is building and he has no idea why he's been feeling vaguely comfortable in cold weather lately.
He is not relevant to this campaign. He is a reminder that there is a larger world.

